{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492488"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:33:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1081"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1081"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.2,0.11,0.03,0.61,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100031"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1081","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1081"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1081"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82423"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"8"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1154"},{"type":"tags","id":"1193"},{"type":"tags","id":"2157"},{"type":"tags","id":"4963"},{"type":"tags","id":"11636"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"699"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2106"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11185"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11518"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43976"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/100031"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman presents to her General Practice clinic with a two-day history of constant right eye discomfort, which she describes as a sensation of pressure and irritation. She notes increased tearing and difficulty seeing clearly, particularly in well-lit environments. There is no history of recent trauma to her eye, and she does not wear contact lenses. She has a history of mild seasonal allergies but denies any other significant medical conditions or medication use. She reports no smoking or alcohol consumption.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears comfortable but demonstrates mild periorbital swelling and erythema in her right eye. Palpation reveals tenderness around the eye. Visual acuity testing shows reduced vision in her right eye compared to her left eye. A slit-lamp examination reveals subtle abnormalities in the anterior chamber.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Acute angle closure glaucoma","Allergic conjunctivitis","Foreign body","Anterior uveitis","Corneal abrasion"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case involves a patient presenting with acute onset eye pain in the context of mild seasonal allergies. The primary consideration is \u003Cstrong\u003Eanterior uveitis\u003C/strong\u003E, characterised by inflammation of the iris and ciliary body. This diagnosis is supported by the patient\u0027s clinical presentation, including eye discomfort, increased tearing, and reduced vision. Photophobia is another common early symptom of anterior uveitis. Furthermore, periorbital swelling, erythema, tenderness, and subtle anterior chamber abnormalities observed during slit-lamp examination align with features typical of anterior uveitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcute angle closure glaucoma\u003C/strong\u003E is less likely due to the absence of severe symptoms such as intense eye pain, nausea, and vomiting. While it can manifest with eye discomfort and reduced vision, acute angle closure glaucoma typically presents with signs of increased intraocular pressure, which are not observed in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllergic conjunctivitis\u003C/strong\u003E is a potential differential diagnosis given the patient\u0027s history of mild seasonal allergies and symptoms such as eye discomfort, tearing, and erythema. However, the presence of periorbital tenderness and reduced vision makes anterior uveitis a more probable explanation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EForeign body sensation \u003C/strong\u003Eis worth considering despite the lack of recent trauma history. Nevertheless, the combination of periorbital swelling, erythema, tenderness, and reduced vision suggests a more complex ocular pathology.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile \u003Cstrong\u003Ecorneal abrasion\u003C/strong\u003E can produce symptoms like eye discomfort, tearing, and reduced vision, the additional signs of periorbital swelling, erythema, and tenderness point toward a deeper ocular issue, such as anterior uveitis, rather than a superficial corneal injury.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dull periocular pain, ocular hyperaemia (red-eye), increased lacrimation and blurry vision are typical symptoms of anterior uveitis."],"references":["Tsirouki T, Dastiridou A, Symeonidis C, Tounakaki O, Brazitikou I, Kalogeropoulos C, et al. A Focus on the Epidemiology of Uveitis. Ocul Immunol Inflamm. 2018;26(1):2-16. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/27467180/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82423"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1081"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"82423","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/82423"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-23T21:00:23+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-23T21:01:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1081"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"100031"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"8","links":{"self":"h